#  Day 73 – Task M-5: Security and Privacy Reporting | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Information Without Communication Has No Governance Value

Day 72 produced the first quarter SSP update — version 1.2 — reflecting the documentation changes driven by M-3 risk response findings. The POA&M was updated with two new items and one closed item. The monitoring log captured 90 days of continuous monitoring activities. The risk register was updated with current threat intelligence.

All of that information exists. Task M-5 is how it reaches the people who need it.

The distinction between monitoring and reporting sounds obvious but is easy to conflate in practice. Monitoring is the ISSO's operational function — running scans, reviewing alerts, updating documentation, executing the continuous monitoring strategy. Reporting is the governance function — translating the outputs of that monitoring work into structured, audience-calibrated communication that enables organizational decision-makers to maintain their risk acceptance with confidence.

An ISSO who monitors diligently but reports inconsistently has created a situation where the AO's authorization decision is based on increasingly stale information. The authorization conditions from Day 67 require quarterly POA&M reporting specifically to prevent this — the AO should not be discovering the CP-2 90-day deadline situation at re-authorization three years from now. They should know it is 12 days from the deadline this week, because the 45-day check-in is scheduled for this week.

Task M-5 formalizes the reporting structure so that information flows from the ISSO to organizational stakeholders on predictable schedules, in formats calibrated to each audience's role and decision-making needs.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task M-5 requires reporting the security status of the system to appropriate organizational officials on an ongoing basis. The reporting must cover the current security posture, the status of ongoing remediation activities, any significant risks or changes, and privacy-related information as applicable under the organization's privacy program. Today I work through the complete M-5 reporting structure for MyClinic's OpenMRS system — who gets what, how often, in what format, and what the first quarterly report to the AO actually contains.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified M-5 today is the difference between security reporting and security documentation.

Documentation — the SSP, SAR, POA&M, monitoring log — is the detailed operational record of the security program. It is comprehensive, technically specific, and primarily useful to the ISSO, assessors, and future security personnel who need to understand the system's security architecture and history.

Reporting is a curated communication product that extracts the governance-relevant information from the documentation and presents it to decision-makers in a form that enables them to fulfill their oversight responsibilities. A quarterly POA&M report to the AO is not the POA&M — it is a structured summary of the POA&M that tells the AO what they need to know to determine whether the authorization remains appropriate.

This distinction matters because the audiences for reports have specific decision-making responsibilities, limited time, and different levels of technical background. The AO needs to know whether authorization conditions are being met and whether the residual risk profile has materially changed. The Health IT Manager needs to know whether their POA&M items are on track and whether any monitoring findings require their involvement. The Compliance Officer needs to know whether any privacy incidents occurred and whether HIPAA notification obligations were triggered. None of these audiences needs — or benefits from — reading the complete SSP and monitoring log.

Effective reporting is curation. The ISSO's job is to understand what each audience needs to make their decisions and provide exactly that — no more, no less.

