### Report 2: Monthly Monitoring Summary — To the Health IT Manager

**Audience:** Health IT Manager (System Owner)
**Frequency:** Monthly
**Purpose:** Keep the System Owner informed of operational security status, POA&M items requiring their involvement, and any findings that need their decision or action

**Format:** Two-page summary. Operational in tone — covers what happened, what requires the Health IT Manager's involvement, and what is coming in the next 30 days.

The monthly report to the Health IT Manager is less formal than the AO quarterly report and more operationally detailed. It includes: a brief current status summary, specific items requiring Health IT Manager action (access review certifications, POA&M items where the Health IT Manager is the owner), upcoming assessment activities that will require their coordination, and any findings from the month's monitoring activities.

A key design principle: the Health IT Manager's report should not require the Health IT Manager to read the monitoring log to understand what the ISSO did. The report synthesizes the month's activities into three sections: "What happened," "What I need from you," and "What's coming up." This respects the Health IT Manager's time and ensures that the items requiring their action are clearly identified rather than buried in a comprehensive update.

---

### Report 3: Privacy Incident Summary — To the Compliance Officer

**Audience:** Compliance Officer
**Frequency:** Monthly summary; immediate notification for any potential HIPAA breach event
**Purpose:** Maintain the Compliance Officer's awareness of privacy-relevant security events and ensure no HIPAA notification obligations are missed

**Format:** Monthly — brief summary of audit log review findings, any ePHI access anomalies, and confirmation that no breach notification is required. The confirmation is as important as the summary — the Compliance Officer needs to know that the ISSO actively evaluated whether any events triggered notification obligations, not just that no notification was sent.

**Immediate notification threshold:** Any GuardDuty finding or security incident that involves or may involve unauthorized access to patient records triggers an immediate notification to the Compliance Officer, before the ISSO has completed the full incident analysis. The Compliance Officer begins the four-factor HIPAA breach assessment in parallel with the ISSO's technical incident investigation. The 60-day HIPAA breach notification window starts from the date the organization knew or should have known about the breach — early Compliance Officer involvement ensures the clock is being tracked from the right starting point.

---

### Report 4: Annual Continuous Monitoring Summary — To the AO

**Audience:** Executive Director (Authorizing Official)
**Frequency:** Annual (per Authorization Condition 4)
**Purpose:** Enable the AO to assess whether the authorization remains appropriate for the next year, whether the continuous monitoring program is functioning, and whether early re-authorization is warranted

**Format:** Structured five-section report covering: year-in-review security posture summary, POA&M item completion progress, vulnerability management trend (12-month scan data), control effectiveness self-assessment with any degradation concerns, and ISSO authorization recommendation (continue, begin early re-authorization planning, or flag material change requiring AO decision).

The annual report is the closest thing to a mid-authorization mini-assessment. It is not conducted by an independent assessor — that is what the formal re-authorization assessment is for. It is the ISSO's structured self-evaluation of whether the security program is functioning as the AO assumed when they authorized the system.

