## What I Am Still Thinking About

The quarterly POA&M report format today — one-page executive summary with full POA&M attached — raises a question about what happens as the authorization period matures and the POA&M grows.

In the first quarter, the POA&M has 12 items. After three years of continuous monitoring, the POA&M may have accumulated 30-40 items, even with regular closures — new monitoring findings, new vulnerability discoveries, new process improvement items. A 40-item POA&M attached to a quarterly report starts to become harder for the AO to use efficiently, even with an executive summary.

One approach I want to develop: a tiered POA&M presentation for the quarterly report that organizes items by governance significance rather than sequential numbering. The AO's view would show: (1) Authorization condition items — these always appear first regardless of how many there are; (2) Moderate severity items — anything above the Low threshold gets explicit attention; (3) Overdue items — anything past its target date regardless of severity; (4) Summary count of on-track Low items — "9 Low items on track, see attached POA&M for details." The AO reviews everything in categories 1-3 in detail and uses the summary count for category 4. This scales to a 40-item POA&M without overwhelming the executive summary.

The tiered presentation ensures that the AO's limited attention goes to the items that most need it — authorization conditions, elevated risks, and overdue commitments — rather than being distributed evenly across all items regardless of their governance significance.

